
🧪 Testing the AI Agent & Lambda Integration (Before Frontend)

📌 Overview


Before integrating the chatbot interface, we first validate the complete backend setup directly inside the Amazon Bedrock Console.

This includes:

✅ AI Agent understanding user queries

✅ Agent following defined instructions (Brain Rules)

✅ Action Group correctly invoking Lambda

✅ Lambda returning proper responses


👉 This step ensures that the AI + backend automation pipeline is fully functional before adding the frontend.

  
🔐 Add Lambda Resource-Based Policy (Mandatory Step)

📌 Why This Is Required


Amazon Bedrock Agent needs permission to invoke the Lambda function.

👉 By default, Lambda blocks external service invocation
👉 So we must add a resource-based policy

🚨 Without This Step

You will get error like:


Access denied while invoking Lambda function
🪜 Steps to Add Permission
Open AWS Console → Lambda
Select your function: BedrockCostAgentTools
Go to Configuration → Permissions
Click Add permissions
Select AWS account
Fill the following:
⚙️ Configuration
Statement ID:
AllowBedrockInvoke

Principal:

bedrock.amazonaws.com

Action:

lambda:InvokeFunction
Click Save
✅ Result
Bedrock Agent can now invoke Lambda
Access denied error is resolved
Agent ↔ Lambda integration works successfully
⚙️ Test Preparation — Create a Chargeable Resource

Before testing, ensure your AWS account has at least one chargeable resource.

👉 If not, create a temporary resource for testing.

🌐 Why Use Elastic IP?
⚡ Easy to create
💰 Chargeable when unattached
🧹 Safe to delete after testing
💸 Cost Note
Approx cost: $0.005/hour
Around: ₹0.40 – ₹0.45/hour

👉 Since it will be deleted during testing, cost is minimal.

  
🪜 Steps to Create Elastic IP
Open AWS Console → EC2
Go to Elastic IPs
Click Allocate Elastic IP address
Keep default settings
Click Allocate
Ensure it shows as Unattached


🧪 Testing the Agent
📍 Where to Test
Open Amazon Bedrock Console
Navigate to:
Agents → CloudFolks-AWS-Admin-Agent
Use the Test Chat Panel (Right Side)

🔍 Test Scenarios

✅ Test 1 — Discover Chargeable Resources

🧑 Input:
Find chargeable resources in ap-south-1
⚙️ Expected Behavior:
Agent calls discover_cost_resources
Lambda scans AWS resources
Results are returned
Agent explains chargeable resources

📌 Example Output:
I found the following chargeable resources:
- Unattached Elastic IP

🗑️ Test 2 — Request Deletion
🧑 Input:
Delete EIP eipalloc-xxxx
⚙️ Expected Behavior:
❌ No immediate deletion
Agent asks for confirmation

📌 Example Output:
Type exactly CONFIRM to proceed

🔐 Test 3 — Confirm Deletion

🧑 Input:

CONFIRM

⚙️ Expected Behavior:
Agent calls delete_cost_resource
Lambda deletes the resource
Agent confirms deletion

📌 Example Output:
Elastic IP successfully deleted
🎯 Why This Step Is Important

This phase ensures:

✅ Agent instructions are working
✅ Action Groups are correctly configured
✅ Lambda functions are executing properly
✅ Safe deletion workflow is enforced

👉 Issues can be fixed here before frontend integration

🚀 Final Result

After successful testing:

✅ AI Agent is fully functional
✅ Backend automation works correctly
✅ Resource discovery & deletion validated
✅ System ready for frontend integration

  
🧠 Key Insight

This step proves that the AI agent can safely automate AWS operations using real infrastructure with human confirmation control.
